---
import ReportLayout from '@/components/ReportLayout.astro';
import FindingCard from '@/components/FindingCard.astro';
import imgAboveFold from '@/assets/reports/myprotein-protein-plp-2026-06-04/above-fold-desktop.png';
import imgFilterTruncation from '@/assets/reports/myprotein-protein-plp-2026-06-04/filter-label-truncation-desktop.png';
import imgSaleRepetition from '@/assets/reports/myprotein-protein-plp-2026-06-04/sale-text-repetition-desktop.png';
import imgProductCards from '@/assets/reports/myprotein-protein-plp-2026-06-04/product-cards-desktop.png';
import imgCategoryChips from '@/assets/reports/myprotein-protein-plp-2026-06-04/category-chips-desktop.png';
---

<ReportLayout title="Protein Powder & Protein Shakes — Myprotein PLP">

  <section class="report-intro">
    <h1 class="report-h1">UX Audit: Protein Powder & Protein Shakes</h1>
    <p class="report-meta">Myprotein Category Page (PLP) &mdash; Audited 4 June 2026</p>
    <p class="report-summary">
      The Protein category listing page has strong above-the-fold trust signals &mdash; Trustpilot
      bar, delivery incentive, app discount, sale countdown &mdash; and well-structured product
      cards with clear pricing hierarchy and correctly labelled Quick Buy buttons. The main
      conversion risks are a filter label truncation that hides a key refinement tool on a
      52-product page, and a sale strapline repeated ~30 times across all product cards that
      produces visual noise and paradoxically undermines the urgency the countdown timer is
      trying to create. Several design system deviations are also present, notably the missing
      mint CTA outer ring.
    </p>
  </section>

  <section class="findings-section">
    <h2 class="section-heading">Findings</h2>

    <!-- HIGH PRIORITY -->

    <FindingCard
      title="&ldquo;Product Ca&hellip;&rdquo; filter label truncated"
      viewport="Desktop"
      priority="high"
      ticketType="engineering"
      ticketable={true}
      findingId="filter-label-truncation"
    >
      <p slot="what">
        The &ldquo;Product Category&rdquo; filter in the sticky filter bar is clipped to
        &ldquo;Product Ca&hellip;&rdquo; at 1440px desktop viewport. The container is too
        narrow for the full label. All other filter labels (Sort, Protein, Flavour, Diet)
        display in full.
        <img src={imgFilterTruncation.src} alt="Filter bar showing 'Product Ca...' truncated label" class="finding-img" />
      </p>
      <p slot="why">
        Users cannot tell what this filter controls without clicking it, adding an extra
        interaction step and reducing the likelihood they use category refinement at all.
        On a page with 52 products, filtering is the primary discovery tool.
      </p>
      <p slot="fix">
        Shorten the label to &ldquo;Category&rdquo; &mdash; this fits comfortably at the
        current column width. Do not use CSS truncation without a tooltip fallback.
        Alternatively, widen the column so the full label is visible.
      </p>
    </FindingCard>

    <FindingCard
      title="Sale strapline repeated ~30 times across product cards"
      viewport="Both"
      priority="high"
      ticketType="engineering"
      ticketable={true}
      findingId="sale-text-repetition"
    >
      <p slot="what">
        &ldquo;IMPACT WEEK SALE | UP TO 80% OFF ALMOST EVERYTHING&rdquo; is injected below
        the Quick Buy button on every product card. A DOM query confirmed
        <code>impactWeekSaleRepetitions: 30</code> on a single page load with the first
        viewport of results visible.
        <img src={imgSaleRepetition.src} alt="Product cards showing repeated IMPACT WEEK SALE strapline under every Quick Buy button" class="finding-img" />
      </p>
      <p slot="why">
        Repetition kills urgency. The sale is already communicated by the top banner and
        countdown timer. Repeating it per-card creates visual clutter, slows scanning of
        product names and prices, and through familiarity makes users blind to it within
        seconds &mdash; the opposite of the intended effect.
      </p>
      <p slot="fix">
        Remove the per-card strapline entirely. The header banner and countdown timer are
        the correct surfaces for this message. If a product-level indicator is needed,
        use a small &ldquo;Sale&rdquo; badge overlay on the product image instead.
      </p>
    </FindingCard>

    <FindingCard
      title="Mint outer ring missing from Quick Buy CTA"
      viewport="Both"
      priority="high"
      ticketType="engineering"
      ticketable={true}
      findingId="missing-mint-ring"
    >
      <p slot="what">
        Computed styles on the Quick Buy button: <code>border: 2px solid oklch(0.3162 0.055061 211.831)</code>
        (the same teal as the button background). The design system requires a mint
        (<code>#94E5B5</code>) outer ring as the brand primary CTA signature. No mint
        ring is present on any Quick Buy button on the page.
      </p>
      <p slot="why">
        The mint ring is the primary visual differentiator between the main CTA and secondary
        actions. Without it, Quick Buy reads as a generic dark pill and loses the brand
        distinctiveness that makes the checkout entry point stand out in the product grid.
      </p>
      <p slot="fix">
        Add <code>outline: 2px solid #94E5B5; outline-offset: 2px;</code> to the Quick Buy
        button component. Confirm this only applies to the primary CTA, not secondary or
        ghost buttons.
      </p>
    </FindingCard>

    <FindingCard
      title="Countdown banner text truncated mid-sentence"
      viewport="Desktop"
      priority="high"
      ticketType="engineering"
      ticketable={true}
      findingId="countdown-text-truncation"
    >
      <p slot="what">
        The sale announcement reads &ldquo;UP TO 80% OFF ALMOST EVERYTHING IMPACT WEEK SALE |
        ENDS IN&hellip;&rdquo; &mdash; the message is cut with an ellipsis before completing.
        The countdown timer sits immediately to the right but the copy that introduces it is
        never finished.
        <img src={imgAboveFold.src} alt="Above-the-fold view showing countdown banner with truncated text" class="finding-img" />
      </p>
      <p slot="why">
        An incomplete sentence undermines trust and leaves users uncertain about the deal
        scope. The countdown timer is anchored to nothing &mdash; users who read the banner
        left-to-right see the message cut before they reach the timer.
      </p>
      <p slot="fix">
        Shorten copy to fit: e.g. &ldquo;Up to 80% off &mdash; ends in&rdquo; then the timer.
        Or reduce font-size from the current 12px and allow the full string to wrap to a second
        line within the banner height.
      </p>
    </FindingCard>

    <!-- MEDIUM PRIORITY -->

    <FindingCard
      title="H1 at 48px pushes products below the fold"
      viewport="Desktop"
      priority="medium"
      ticketType="design"
      ticketable={true}
      findingId="h1-size-plp"
    >
      <p slot="what">
        The H1 &ldquo;Protein Powder & Protein Shakes&rdquo; renders at
        <code>font-size: 48px; font-weight: 700</code>. With a global nav (two rows),
        trust bar, sale banner, breadcrumb, sub-nav chips, and sticky filter bar all above
        it, the first product row is partially below the fold at a 900px viewport height.
      </p>
      <p slot="why">
        Products are the conversion driver on a PLP. Every pixel of non-product chrome delays
        the user reaching what they came to buy. A 48px heading is appropriate for editorial
        landing pages, not a product grid.
      </p>
      <p slot="fix">
        Reduce H1 to 32px on all PLP templates. The heading still anchors the page category
        but gives the product grid significantly more above-the-fold presence.
      </p>
    </FindingCard>

    <FindingCard
      title="Card border-radius is 16px, design token specifies 12px"
      viewport="Both"
      priority="medium"
      ticketType="engineering"
      ticketable={true}
      findingId="card-border-radius"
    >
      <p slot="what">
        Computed <code>border-radius: 16px</code> on product cards. The design token for
        cards is <code>12px</code>. This is a hardcoded override, not a token reference.
      </p>
      <p slot="why">
        Inconsistency with other card surfaces across the site that correctly use the 12px
        token. At scale (52 cards per page) the deviation is visually noticeable.
      </p>
      <p slot="fix">
        Update the product card component to use the <code>rounded-card</code> design token
        (12px). Remove the hardcoded value.
      </p>
    </FindingCard>

    <FindingCard
      title="Quick Buy font-size 16px, token specifies 14px for buttons"
      viewport="Both"
      priority="medium"
      ticketType="engineering"
      ticketable={true}
      findingId="button-font-size"
    >
      <p slot="what">
        Computed <code>font-size: 16px; font-weight: 700</code> on the Quick Buy button.
        The design system specifies all buttons at <code>14px Bold</code>.
      </p>
      <p slot="why">
        The oversized label makes the button feel slightly heavy relative to the card
        content, and is inconsistent with other buttons across the site using the correct
        14px token.
      </p>
      <p slot="fix">
        Update the button component CSS to <code>font-size: 14px</code>.
      </p>
    </FindingCard>

    <FindingCard
      title="Countdown timer has no aria-live attribute"
      viewport="Both"
      priority="medium"
      ticketType="engineering"
      ticketable={true}
      findingId="countdown-aria-live"
    >
      <p slot="what">
        The countdown timer element ticks every second but carries no <code>aria-live</code>
        attribute. Confirmed via DevTools: <code>countdownAriaLive: null</code>.
      </p>
      <p slot="why">
        WCAG 4.1.3 (Status Messages) requires time-sensitive status updates to be surfaced
        to assistive technologies. Screen reader users receive no announcement of the sale
        urgency signal.
      </p>
      <p slot="fix">
        Add <code>aria-live="polite"</code> to the countdown wrapper. Use a throttled update
        (e.g. announce once per minute: &ldquo;Sale ends in X minutes&rdquo;) rather than
        announcing every second tick, to avoid spamming screen reader users.
      </p>
    </FindingCard>

    <FindingCard
      title="Sub-category chips show no active or selected state"
      viewport="Both"
      priority="medium"
      ticketType="design"
      ticketable={false}
      findingId="subcategory-chip-active-state"
    >
      <p slot="what">
        The sub-category chips (Whey Protein, Protein Isolate, Protein Blends, Collagen,
        Vegan Protein) are visually identical regardless of which page the user is on.
        No chip appears highlighted or selected on the parent protein category page.
        <img src={imgCategoryChips.src} alt="Sub-category chips with no active state shown" class="finding-img" />
      </p>
      <p slot="why">
        Users lose navigation context on a page with 52 products across multiple sub-types.
        Without a clear selected state, users cannot tell where they are within the category
        hierarchy and are more likely to use back/forward rather than the chip nav.
      </p>
      <p slot="fix">
        Design an active chip state (e.g. filled teal background, white text, matching the
        nav active pattern) and apply it to the chip corresponding to the current URL.
        Needs a design spec before engineering can implement.
      </p>
    </FindingCard>

    <FindingCard
      title="Page &lt;title&gt; and H1 are inconsistent"
      viewport="Both"
      priority="medium"
      ticketType="engineering"
      ticketable={true}
      findingId="title-h1-mismatch"
    >
      <p slot="what">
        <code>&lt;title&gt;</code>: &ldquo;Premium Protein Powders & Supplements | Myprotein UK&rdquo;<br />
        <code>&lt;h1&gt;</code>: &ldquo;Protein Powder & Protein Shakes&rdquo;
      </p>
      <p slot="why">
        Inconsistency between page title and H1 creates a mismatch for screen reader users
        (who hear the page announced differently from what they read) and signals mixed
        intent to search engines about the primary keyword.
      </p>
      <p slot="fix">
        Align the page title to reflect the H1: &ldquo;Protein Powder & Protein Shakes |
        Myprotein UK&rdquo;. Alternatively, if the current title performs better in search,
        update the H1 to match it.
      </p>
    </FindingCard>

    <!-- LOW PRIORITY -->

    <FindingCard
      title="Sort button border-radius is 5px (off token scale)"
      viewport="Both"
      priority="low"
      ticketType="engineering"
      ticketable={true}
      findingId="sort-border-radius"
    >
      <p slot="what">
        Computed <code>border-radius: 5px</code> on the Sort filter dropdown trigger.
        Valid token values are 4, 8, 12, 16, 24, 32, 56, 9999px. The value 5px is a
        hardcoded override not on the scale.
      </p>
      <p slot="why">Minor inconsistency in the filter bar.</p>
      <p slot="fix">
        Update to the nearest token: <code>border-radius: 4px</code> or
        <code>8px</code>, whichever matches the intended visual style.
      </p>
    </FindingCard>

  </section>

  <section class="prose-section">
    <h2 class="section-heading">Design Consistency</h2>
    <p>
      Figtree is correctly applied as the computed font family across all inspected elements
      (headings, body text, and buttons). The Quick Buy button correctly uses
      <code>border-radius: 32px</code> and <code>font-weight: 700</code>, matching their
      respective tokens. However, several deviations exist: product card
      <code>border-radius: 16px</code> vs the 12px card token; button
      <code>font-size: 16px</code> vs the 14px button token; the Sort trigger uses an
      off-scale 5px radius; and critically the mint <code>#94E5B5</code> outer ring is
      absent from all Quick Buy buttons. The sale banner background
      (<code>rgb(217, 66, 15)</code>) is the brand coral used for promotional surfaces,
      which is appropriate. The trust bar and card backgrounds share
      <code>oklch(0.9654 0.006 75.41)</code> (warm near-white), consistent with the
      site-wide surface token.
    </p>
  </section>

  <section class="prose-section">
    <h2 class="section-heading">Accessibility Notes</h2>
    <p>
      Quick Buy buttons carry correctly formed <code>aria-label</code> values including
      the product name (e.g. <code>aria-label="QUICK BUY Impact Whey Protein Milkshake"</code>),
      which correctly disambiguates repeated CTAs for screen reader users. Wishlist buttons
      similarly carry descriptive labels
      (e.g. <code>aria-label="Add Impact Whey Protein Milkshake to wishlist"</code>).
      Product images have alt text populated with flavour variant names
      (e.g. &ldquo;Vimto&rdquo;, &ldquo;Snickers&rdquo;) &mdash; acceptable in context
      but could be more descriptive (e.g. &ldquo;Clear Whey Protein &mdash; Vimto
      flavour&rdquo;). The countdown timer lacks <code>aria-live</code>, a WCAG 4.1.3 gap.
      The all-caps sale strapline under product cards renders at 12px, below the recommended
      minimum body text size of 14px, posing a legibility challenge for low-vision users.
      Primary CTA contrast (white on dark teal) visually passes WCAG AA.
    </p>
  </section>

  <section class="prose-section">
    <h2 class="section-heading">Conversion Summary</h2>
    <p>
      The path to Quick Buy is short and well-structured: users land on a page with immediate
      pricing context (current price, was price, saving amount), star ratings with review
      counts, Best Seller badging, and a prominent CTA. The trust bar above the fold
      (free delivery threshold, Trustpilot 4.4-star rating, app discount) reduces checkout
      anxiety before a user has even seen a product. The two highest-impact friction points
      are the filter label truncation &mdash; which hides the most useful refinement tool
      on a 52-product page &mdash; and the repeated sale strapline that clutters the grid
      and trains users to ignore all promotional messaging. Fixing these two issues, plus
      adding the mint CTA ring, are the changes most likely to have an immediate positive
      effect on add-to-bag rate.
    </p>
  </section>

  <section class="prose-section">
    <h2 class="section-heading">Recommended Implementation Order</h2>
    <ol class="recommendations">
      <li>Remove the per-card &ldquo;IMPACT WEEK SALE&rdquo; strapline from all product cards &mdash; engineering, low effort, highest noise reduction</li>
      <li>Fix &ldquo;Product Ca&hellip;&rdquo; filter truncation &mdash; rename label to &ldquo;Category&rdquo; in CMS/template</li>
      <li>Add mint <code>#94E5B5</code> outer ring to Quick Buy button &mdash; one CSS rule change</li>
      <li>Fix countdown banner copy truncation &mdash; shorten copy to fit container</li>
      <li>Add <code>aria-live="polite"</code> with throttled announcement to countdown timer</li>
      <li>Reduce H1 font-size from 48px to 32px on all PLP templates &mdash; design sign-off first</li>
      <li>Design and implement active state for sub-category chips &mdash; design spec then engineering</li>
      <li>Align page <code>&lt;title&gt;</code> with H1 &mdash; CMS/template update</li>
      <li>Fix card border-radius (16px &rarr; 12px) and button font-size (16px &rarr; 14px) &mdash; token cleanup sprint</li>
      <li>Fix sort button border-radius (5px &rarr; 4px or 8px) &mdash; token cleanup sprint</li>
    </ol>
  </section>

</ReportLayout>

<style is:global>
  .finding-card code {
    font-family: Menlo, Monaco, 'Courier New', monospace;
    font-size: 12px;
    background: var(--color-bg-muted);
    padding: 1px 5px;
    border-radius: 4px;
    color: var(--color-text-heading);
  }
  .finding-img {
    display: block;
    margin-top: 12px;
    width: 100%;
    border-radius: 8px;
    border: 1px solid rgba(0,57,66,0.1);
  }
</style>

<style>
  .report-intro { margin-bottom: 40px; }
  .report-h1 { font-size: 26px; font-weight: 800; color: var(--color-text-heading); line-height: 1.25; margin-bottom: 6px; }
  .report-meta { font-size: 13px; color: var(--color-text-body); opacity: 0.65; margin-bottom: 14px; }
  .report-summary { font-size: 15px; line-height: 1.7; color: var(--color-text-body); max-width: 680px; }
  .findings-section { margin-bottom: 48px; }
  .section-heading { font-size: 18px; font-weight: 700; color: var(--color-text-heading); margin-bottom: 20px; padding-bottom: 10px; border-bottom: 2px solid rgba(0, 57, 66, 0.1); }
  .prose-section { margin-bottom: 36px; }
  .prose-section p { font-size: 15px; line-height: 1.7; color: var(--color-text-body); }
  .recommendations { padding-left: 20px; display: flex; flex-direction: column; gap: 10px; }
  .recommendations li { font-size: 14px; line-height: 1.6; color: var(--color-text-body); }
</style>
